# .trivyignore
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CVEs accepted as known risk, with documented justification.
#
# Format:
#   CVE-YYYY-NNNNN  # Justification: why accepted, when to revisit
#
# Trivy uses this file when run with --ignorefile .trivyignore
# The GitHub Actions workflow passes it via trivyignores: .trivyignore
#
# IMPORTANT: This file should be reviewed every quarter or after any major
# image base change. A suppressed CVE that becomes exploitable in context is
# still a real risk regardless of what's in this file.
#
# To list all CVEs currently being suppressed:
#   grep -v '^#' .trivyignore | grep -v '^$'
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Example (uncomment and fill in when you have real accepted-risk CVEs):
#
# CVE-2023-XXXXX   # pkg: openssl, fixed in: 3.x, status: no fix available in
#                  # node:18-alpine yet; network not exposed; accepted until
#                  # upstream alpine updates. Revisit: 2026-06-01
#
# CVE-2023-YYYYY   # pkg: some-transitive-dep, fixAvailable: false, severity:
#                  # HIGH but requires local access — lab env only, not
#                  # internet-reachable. Revisit: 2026-06-01

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Notes on the gating strategy:
#   The pipeline fails on HIGH/CRITICAL where ignore-unfixed: true, meaning
#   Trivy only fails if a fix EXISTS but hasn't been applied. CVEs with no
#   upstream fix available won't fail the build — but should be tracked here
#   with a revisit date so they don't become permanently ignored.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── ACCEPTED RISK ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# CVE-2026-33671  pkg: picomatch 4.0.3 → fixed in 4.0.4
#   path:   /usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/tinyglobby/node_modules/picomatch/
#   chain:  npm → tinyglobby → picomatch (npm-internal glob tooling)
#   impact: ReDoS via crafted extglob patterns in picomatch
#   why accepted:
#     - picomatch is used by npm's tinyglobby for file discovery during package
#       operations. npm does not run in the production container — the CMD is
#       `node /app/index.js` as a non-root user. There is no code path that
#       passes user-controlled input to picomatch at runtime.
#     - picomatch 4.0.4 has been released but has not yet propagated into
#       npm@latest's bundled dependency tree. This cannot be patched via
#       package.json overrides as it is npm's internal transitive dep.
#   action: monitor npm releases; remove this entry once npm@latest bundles
#           tinyglobby with picomatch >= 4.0.4 and rebuild the image.
#   revisit: 2026-07-05
CVE-2026-33671
